My newly re-designed apartment is a gem amidst the vibrancy of central Brixton: a haven of exposed brickwork, warm pine floorboards & clear, neat, contemporary lines which extend to the uber modern kitchen and travertine stone clad bathroom. Total surface area of 65 sqm on the Market's doorstep & a 3 min walk to Brixton Underground & Railway station.

The space
My apartment is a spacious two bed located on the second floor of a listed Victorian residential building dating back to the 1880's and crowned with a breathtaking roof garden. It's conveniently located bang in the middle of central Brixton, a mere two minute walk from the Underground and railway stations with links to Oxford Circus in 10 mns and to Victoria in 7 respectively. neighborhood_overview:
Time Out London have an online guide to Brixton and all there is to do in the neighbourhood:

(website hidden)

Please note that Brixton Market is made of two different parts:

-Market Row is located where my building is (entrance to the left) - personal favourites include Kuku (Persian cafe with delicious cakes and sumptuous lattes), Yum-D (fantastic, authentic Thai food – bring your own wine/beer), Bukowski (US carnivores' haven)

-Brixton Village is located across the railway (up on Coldhabour Lane) - personal favourites include Honest Burgers (there's usually a humongous queue), The Agile Rabbit (pizzas & live music), Elephant (tasty and cheap Pakistani curry food), Jalisco (back-to-basics tex-mex: burritos, tacos, salads and margaritas)

More details on the market itself:

(website hidden)

Good pubs in the neighbourhood include The Trinity Arms (on Trinity Gardens, off Brixton Road via Brighton Terrace: (websit
host_about: A Londoner of 25 years, after all this time I am still making the most of everything the greatest city in the northern hemisphere has on offer, from traditional pubs to evenings of Shakespeare's classics at the Globe theatre, music festivals on the Southbank to contemporary art exhibitions in East London, gigs at the Brixton Academy to street food in Soho etc. - one can never be blasé in London! I'm also a keen traveller, out of the country on a fortnightly basis or so, both in Europe and the Americas - with a marked obsession for Sudamerica (Chile! Brasil!). Food is extremely important to me and one of the perks of being on the road so often - I love recreating in my own kitchen what I've treated my tastebuds to on my travels. I work in publishing so the written word and the arts are  of huge importance to me and a constant source of pleasure, exploration and furthering of knowledge. Socialising in another huuuuge aspect of my life, friends, friends of friends, future friends...bring them all under the same roof! I live in one of London's most exciting neighbourhoods and I am very attached to it - as I am to my gorgeous house which I re designed myself and is both a source of pride and a cosy home.

It is 3rd floor and there is no lift so please note that it is quite a walk upstairs.

The flat has 2 bedrooms, 1 bathroom, 1 kitchen, a lounge and a balcony.

It has a simple, modern but comfortable interior, wooden floors and far infrared heaters.

The space
The flat is on the 3rd floor with some views to the city of London, Canary wharf and Regents Canal.
Please note that there is no lift in the building so its quite a walk upstairs (especially with luggage).
The flat is 2 bedroom 1 bathroom with kitchen and lounge and a balcony. The decor is modern and comfortable.

The guest bedroom is the one closest to the entrance.

1 double bed
1 chair
1 talbe

1 chest of drawers

neighborhood_overview: A mixed residential neighborhood only 1.4 kilometers from City of London.  It's considered the East End of London. Queen Mary university is 6mins walk, Ragged School Museum is 5 mins walk. Brick Lane Tower of London and City of London are 10mins on the tube or 20-30mins by bus depending on traffic. We are 30mins walk away from Victoria park and Canary wharf. 8mins on DLR from Tower Bridge/of London (or over an hour walk along the river if you have time for that) .  There are few pubs, local restaurants and coffee houses nearby. Regents Canal is 200 yards from the flat and we are less then 5mins away from Mile End Stadium (they have gym, sauna and pool facilities). There are many cycling/walking routes crossing here, and 2 of the most popular running/jogging routes are nearby along with the official London Marathon route.

name: Rental unit in Greater London · ★4.78 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 shared bath
description:
Amazing double room bright, clean, central London flat. 2 mins walk to London Borough Station, 5 mins walk to London Bridge station, very close to Borough Market, The Shard, Tate Modern, River Thames, Shakespeare's world-famous Globe Theatre, Tower Bridge, The Tower of London, and the tube stations, (Borough, London Bridge, Elephant & Castle). You’ll love it because of its fantastic location for getting anywhere in London. It's good for couples, solo adventurers, and business travellers.

The space
Like the perfect pot of afternoon tea, Southwark has been culturally steeping for centuries. The neighbourhood is home to many of the city’s iconic landmarks—London’s most famous bridges, buildings, and museums are located in Southwark. Crisscross the Thames via the Tower, Millennium, or London bridges and be rewarded with panoramic views of history abutting modernity—Southwark boasts Shakespeare’s Globe Theatre, the Tate Modern museum, London’s famous Borough market,
neighborhood_overview:
Our Flat is situated in a conservation area at the heart of Borough and London Bridge just behind the hustle and bustle of Borough High Street.

Borough Market, London bridge, Shards, The London Eye, Tower of London and Tower Bridge, Westminster Parliament, Big Ben, Westminster Abbey, The City are all a short walk away with a huge mix of galleries, shops, markets, bars, pubs and restaurants. from casual to Michelin star fine dining.

You can also find many interesting local attractions in the neighbourhood including Piccadilly and Soho for its bars and nightlife, Borough and Spitalfields' for their markets, restaurants and shops, the wonderful London Eye and Herry Potter London Tour the British Museum, perfect for children young or old!

For people visiting or working at the London Bridge, coming to Kings College, the Guys and St Thomas Hospital we are just a 3 minute walk away.

The space
This newly-refurbished apartment is above our house. It has its own entrance and free parking on the premises.

Separate master bedroom with a small double bed and an en-suite shower room.

The living room has a smart TV and a sofa, as well as a sofa bed that can accommodate a third person / two small children. Air conditioning unit available. Washer dryer, iron and ironing board provided.

neighborhood_overview:
Hampton heated open air pool is open 365 days a year and is a two-minute walk, as is a footpath leading into Bushy Park, Henry the VIII's former hunting ground, home of the original Park Run, where you can see deer, take a walk, enjoy refreshments at the Pheasantry Café or indeed join the weekly Saturday morning Park Run.

The river Thames is about a 5-minute walk, where you can hire a boat or take the foot ferry across the river (boat hire and ferry available April - October).

Hampton Court Palace is a seven-minute bus ride or a twenty five-minute walk through the Royal Park.

There are two pubs serving food and an Indian Restaurant within five- minute walk.

description: Made in Chelsea or not, Sloane Square is your West London haven and hideaway. Tucked above a stylish textiles store, the stock brick of this corner building has been restored to keep its original charm. Start your stay right by whipping up a meal in your fully equipped kitchen, sourcing fresh produce from the Pimlico Road Farmers Market on your doorstep. Then, take to the streets of Chelsea to peruse blushing boutiques and sample the chic cafes dotted around the neighborhood. Breathe in that fresh English air with a wander through Ranelagh Gardens or a trip across the Chelsea bridge to discover Battersea Park. For some indoor entertainment, admire the contemporary artwork of the Saatchi Gallery or enjoy an innovative performance at The Royal Court Theatre. As long as you're in this area known for its elevated eateries, snag a reservation at Hunan, Enoteca Turi, or La Poule au Pot to see what the fuss is about. Back at Sloane Square, each space comes with comfortable beds, elevated desi
neighborhood_overview: Endless rows of elegant townhouses. Lush green gardens and squares. An array of superior fine-dining restaurants. It’s no secret that Belgravia is one of London’s most desirable neighborhoods. Spend your day browsing the boutique shops or sipping coffee in one of the many quaint cafés. Head to Eccleston Yards for their Sunday craft market and outdoor aerobics. For your culture fix, Belgravia Gallery has an impressive collection of royal art and photography. For a taste of the finer things in life — this is Belgravia.

neighborhood_overview: Brunswick Quay is set within Surrey Quays (formerly Surrey Docks), a largely residential area of Rotherhithe in south-east London, part of London Borough of Southwark. The are has a long history as a port, with many shipyards from Elizabethan times until the early 20th century and with working docks until the 1970s. Following the closure of docks, the area along the river was redeveloped as housing through a mix of warehouse conversions and new-build developments. The only surviving areas of open water were Greenland Dock, South Dock, part of Canada Dock (renamed Canada Water), remnants of Norway Dock, and a basin renamed Surrey Water.

King’s Cross might be best known for its bustling train stations linking London to other parts of the country, as well as the continent, but a recent host of developments have regenerated the area, with new restaurants, bars and pubs popping up.

Shop at the brand new Coal Drops Yard and, if you end up feeling peckish, wander over to Kerb food market or the restaurants that line Granary Square. neighborhood_overview:
King’s Cross might be best known for its bustling train stations linking London to other parts of the country, as well as the continent, but a recent host of developments have regenerated the area, with new restaurants, bars and pubs popping up.

There are plenty of other things to do as well, with outstanding clubs, music venues and museums nearby, much-loved green spaces and a pretty stretch of Regent’s Canal, all of which makes King’s Cross an ace destination in its own right. If you’re feeling cultured, pop to the famous British Library which boasts an impressive events calendar packed with exhibitions and talks all year long. Shop at the brand new Coal Drops Yard and, if you end up feeling peckish, wander over to Kerb food market or the restaurants that line Granary Square. We absolutely understand if you need to make a detour to King’s Cross station for your snap at Harry Potter’s Platform 9¾

neighborhood_overview:
The house is handily located for guests hoping to visit either the Excel Centre of Westfield Shopping Centre. Both are less than a 15 minute drive away.

It's also not far from Wanstead High Street, voted England’s best small high street 2015.

The Red Lion pub by Central Park is by far and away our favourite local. It has a great selection of delicious beers and super friendly staff.

There are some nice cafés in the area too, including The Central Park Cafe on the edge of the park. It sells the most delicious sourdough bread.

If you'd rather eat at home, we love The Wanstead Kitchen, Krapow and The Sauce for delicious takeaway food.

There are lots of little corner shops for picking up essentials but if you're looking for a bit more choice, Tesco Express is just a 15 minute walk away.

Ideally located, off a quiet street, just a few minutes walk from the High Strees of High Street Kensington. You'll be spoilt for choice for eateries and shopping on the doorstep but your also a stones throw from South Kensington and many of the main London attractions - Hyde Park, The Royal Albert Hall, Holland Park, The Natural History Museum and the V&A, which are all within walking distance. 


Kensington itself is famous for its boutique shopping and its artisan cafe culture. There are plenty of wonderful food spots just moments away from the property (we highly recommend the Fait Maison cafe opposite) and you won't be short of options for a quality tea and cake pitt-stop or just a seat in a local cafe to relax and watch the locals going about daily life. Coffee lovers will not be disappointed and there are an array of chocolate shops, ice cream parlous and other treats for those who enjoy the sweeter things. host_about: Hello. We are a small team of dancers and artists that specialise in the creative industries, working with amazing people and unique individual homes. Our mission is to make sure that both guests and hosts have the best possible experience of sharing their homes. All the properties we list here are cleaned and prepared by our team before arrival with fresh linen and towels provided during each stay.  We do our best to always have someone to meet you at the apartment to hand over the keys and and offer advice and guidance about the local area. We like to keep the lines of communication open so my team and I are always a message or call away. When we're not busy with Property Management, we love to take some time out to enjoy this lovely city. Favourite places are the Royal Opera House and the Serpentine Lido in Hyde Park. We love to dance and seeing shows in the west end is one of the highlights for the team of being in London. We like to travel in style but are equally happy up a mountain or in the country as we are in the city. We love to get lost and explore new places by simply soaking up the atmosphere.

neighborhood_overview:
Spacious apartment is situated in one of London's coolest neighborhoods -
Clerkenwell in Islington which has everything. The area is full of trendy bars, restaurants & designer shops and minutes away from the local canal. It's also very family friendly for kids as situated on a private road with a playground a 2 minute walk aroud the corner giving you the best of everything.
This area is possibly the best location for all corners of London, as it's so central.
The area is a mix of historical sights and tourist attractions and also home to a thriving design industry, so there are lots of creatives buzzing around the area from Monday through to Friday and it''s very peaceful and quiet at the weekends. Thanks to that creative mix of designers and architects, there's a choice of cool bars and rated restaurants all within walking distance of the apartment.
host_about: We are a professional couple with two young daughters living in central London. We have lived here happily for 12 years but as our family is growing, we sadly need to move. However, we are excited to share this great apartment with visitors so they can experience urban London just as we have.
